    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Draw on Canvas</title>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="myCanvas" width="500" height="500"></canvas>
    <script src="draw.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

JavaScript:
```
const canvas = document.getElementById('myCanvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

let isDrawing = false;
let lastX = 0;
let lastY = 0;

canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
    isDrawing = true;
    lastX = e.clientX - canvas.offsetLeft;
    lastY = e.clientY - canvas.offsetTop;
});

canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', (e) => {
    isDrawing = false;
    lastX = undefined;
    lastY = undefined;
});

canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
    if (isDrawing) {
        const x = e.clientX - canvas.offsetLeft;
        const y = e.clientY - canvas.offsetTop;

        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.moveTo(lastX, lastY);
        ctx.lineTo(x, y);
        ctx.stroke();

        lastX = x;
        lastY = y;
    }
});
```

This code creates a canvas element with an id of "myCanvas". It also includes a JavaScript file called "draw.js" that contains the logic for drawing on the canvas.

The JavaScript code sets up event listeners for the mouse events (mousedown, mouseup, and mousemove). When the user clicks and drags the mouse, the code draws a line on the canvas.

